      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the principal balance seems to play hide and seek with your hard-earned money. It's like a mischievous goblin, always lurking in the shadows, ready to snatch a bit of your gold each month. When you make your monthly payments, a portion of that gold goes to the goblin (interest), while the rest goes to the principal. The goblin loves to feast on the interest, but only a little bit of your gold actually goes to the principal. It's like trying to fill a leaking bucket with a sieve; the goblin (interest) keeps draining it, making it seem like your gold isn't really going anywhere. But don't worry, every little bit you pay goes to the goblin, slowly weakening its power over your loan. Keep at it, and eventually, you'll see the goblin's influence diminish, and your principal balance will start to shrink. Keep your eyes peeled for the goblin's tricks, and you'll soon outsmart it!",
